post_text:
Reminder about tonights game:

We need to have everyone in our stadium practicing social distancing to help keep our community and students safe by being able to offer our activities. We have had several new cases in our community this week.
Guidelines:
- Sit in family units that at 6' apart
- Spectators are asked to wear a mask to help reduce community spread
-If you don't feel well, stay home
-If you are quarantined, you must stay home

*A person you may sit with at the game could come down with COVID in the future and being around them closer than 6' for 15 minutes with or without a mask would result in a person needing to quarantine for 14 days. Please be cognizant of others and help slow down the spread.

Now more than ever, it is SO important we be there for one another and take steps to prevent suicide. Whether you have struggled with suicide yourself or lost a loved one, know that you are not alone! Reach out to your school counselor, a friend, or loved one if you're struggling or know someone who is struggling.
National Suicide Prevention Lifeline
1-800-273-TALK. Crisis Text Line
Text TALK to 741741. #NHtribe

HS Activities/Athletics will continue in our Hybrid model. Students will not be allowed in the building until practice time or when a team leaves. We will need to continue to wear masks and social distance to limit the risk of our activities having to quarantine both inside and outside. That means everyone needs to maintain 6' distance between another person!

Going to a distance learning model for the high school for all students would result in all activities and athletics needing to be shut down. Let's do our part to help reduce the chances of that happening!

post_text: Students in Mr Rude’s social studies classes started their journey in oratory this week. They are learning about the Podium Points and the Rhetorical Triangle as they participate in the Fords Theater National Oratory Fellowship that Mr. Rude has been a involved with for the past three years. The students made three sentence speeches, and then crafted them into short arguments for topics of their choosing. Topics ranged from lunch food, dogs vs. cats, and everything in between.

MS/HS Pick-up

I wanted to send a reminder as we have had cars backing up traffic or even stopping on the road. Please do not do this as this causes an issue for all involved. Students not riding the bus will not be released from school until the buses have left campus. Our goal is to have buses departing for the elementary playground around 3:15. Please do not arrive any earlier than this, if you do come early do not enter the loading zone, please use ASH Drive across from the school and wait to drive through to pick your student up after buses have departed.

Thank you for helping with this issue and keeping everyone safe!

post_text:
To keep our students and fans safe please be aware and follow our guidelines for attending all New Hampton Athletic Events:

1. It is required that everyone attending indoor activities wears a mask.
2. It is strongly encouraged that everyone attending outdoor activities wears a mask.
3. We will be sitting in every other row of seats to promote social distancing.
4. Do not sit in rows that have colored tape on the end seat.
5. For student sections, we ask that the students follow the every other row regulation and also sit by grade levels.
6. Please sit with people you live with or already spend time together.
7. Please be respectful of others and their beliefs and feelings.
8. By working together and following a few guidelines we hope to make this a safe experience for everyone.
9. Thank you for supporting our students.

HS Students:

We are SO excited to have you all back with us as we start the 20-21 school year. We wanted to give you a heads up and let you know that the absolute last day to make schedule changes this year will be Wednesday, August 26th. No exceptions.

Typically, you have about a week to 'try your schedule out' and make changes as needed, but because the schedule looks different this year, you won't have as many days once the school year starts to make changes.

Please take a look at your schedule if you haven't already done so and let Mrs. Maas know what/if any changes need to be made.

If you're having issues viewing your schedule or understanding how your schedule is going to work this year, please reach out!

post_text: Students enrolled in Bio 168: Anatomy and Physiology I : This course will be offered in a HYBRID fashion throughout the full semester. During the 1st quarter (Aug. 24-Oct. 23), class will be entirely ONLINE while during 2nd quarter (Oct. 26-Jan. 15), class will be as scheduled during 4th period (Block 2) in a FACE TO FACE format. During the ONLINE portion, class materials will largely be delivered to you through Schoology, however, it will be important that you stop in on the first day of school to be issued your corresponding textbook from Mrs. Leistikow!!

On Monday May 4th there will be 150 more!

New Hampton students, come get a free lilac bush donated from the Chickasaw County Soil and Water Conservation District and Morris Landscaping tomorrow on the Elementary Playground from 11:30-12:30! Thank you for the donation and looking forward to seeing pictures of families planting these around Chickasaw County! Planting a bush will help students develop an appreciation for one of our most important natural resources.
text:
On Monday May 4th there will be 150 more!

New Hampton students, come get a free lilac bush donated from the Chickasaw County Soil and Water Conservation District and Morris Landscaping tomorrow on the Elementary Playground from 11:30-12:30! Thank you for the donation and looking forward to seeing pictures of families planting these around Chickasaw County! Planting a bush will help students develop an appreciation for one of our most important natural resources.

post_text: Thank you for all the help and donations!

ESPN.COM
The Man in the Red Bandana | Watch ESPN

New Hampton Middle School
April 29 at 6:12 PM ·

We have a very special guest joining our Zoom on Tuesday, May 5th at 11am. It's someone that we have talked about before. His name is Tom Rinaldi and he is a reporter for ESPN. He is the man that put together The Man in the Red Bandana. 7th graders- This is the guy we were going to interview in the fall but it didn't work out. 8th graders- We have watched this in class and Tom is a master researcher.

Our focus will be on primary source research, with his work on the ESPN piece being the case study.

Please watch the video linked below before we meet with him on Tuesday. This Zoom is open to NHMS 7th and 8th graders.

https://www.espn.com/watch/player/_/id/11505494/lang/en

New Hampton Middle School
April 29 at 8:27 AM ·

Parents and Students:

This closure has been tough on parents, students, teachers, and staff. Let’s find a positive way to support each other! The week of May 4th-May 8th is teacher appreciation week. We are not going to be able to see our teachers to thank them for all they do for us due to the physical school being closed. Let’s create a shower of appreciation to our teachers thanking them for all they do through emails, notes, videos, pictures, or other ways. You can add comments on Facebook or send responses to Mr. Manson m_manson@new-hampton.k12.ia.us and I will post on Facebook for everyone to see our community support of our teachers!

#NHTribe

New Hampton Police Department
March 3 at 5:12 PM ·

This morning (3/3/2020), the New Hampton Police Department was contacted by the New Hampton High School in regards to a "statement" that was made by a student. As with any threat, this was taken seriously and is under further investigation. Action has been taken; however since this involves a juvenile, no further information can be released. It has been determined that there is no danger to students and staff in regards to this incident.

post_text: I see a lot of posts related to our notification of the verbal threat incident at the high school this morning. We elected to use social media as we felt that was the quickest way to get the word out on the incident to our parents and community members. Some posts that have been shared since are simply inaccurate information and some posts appear to only have the purpose of trying to incite others. If someone makes a threat and the police are notified, it’s highly unlikely that the student will simply be “sent home”. If this was your child, you would want the district to preserve and protect his or her privacy as we do for every student. As soon as the district learned of the threat, we responded appropriately and fully addressed it with the assistance of law enforcement to make sure it is properly handled and all students and staff remain safe.

post_text: Zoe Worple and Ivan Camarillo were project leaders for a Breast Cancer Awareness fundraiser. The event raised $665.00, which was donated to the Beyond Pink non-profit organization based out of the Waterloo/Cedar Falls area. This organization supports breast cancer patients in all of Northeast Iowa with expenses beyond what insurance covers. President Dee Hughes and Vice President Mary Mullnix travelled to New Hampton for the presentation of the donation check on Wednesday, December 18, 2019. Present in the photo are Mary Mullnix, Ivan Camarillo, Zoe Worple, Dee Hughes, Claire Quirk (Interact co-leader), Kris Ward (Faculty Sponsor), Sandra Russ (Faculty Sponsor), Emma Rosonke (Interact co-leader), and Dr. Sarah Updegraff. . #NHtribe
text: Zoe Worple and Ivan Camarillo were project leaders for a Breast Cancer Awareness fundraiser. The event raised $665.00, which was donated to the Beyond Pink non-profit organization based out of the Waterloo/Cedar Falls area. This organization supports breast cancer patients in all of Northeast Iowa with expenses beyond what insurance covers. President Dee Hughes and Vice President Mary Mullnix travelled to New Hampton for the presentation of the donation check on Wednesday, December 18, 2019. Present in the photo are Mary Mullnix, Ivan Camarillo, Zoe Worple, Dee Hughes, Claire Quirk (Interact co-leader), Kris Ward (Faculty Sponsor), Sandra Russ (Faculty Sponsor), Emma Rosonke (Interact co-leader), and Dr. Sarah Updegraff. . #NHtribe

shared_text:
Eichenberger's Kindergarten
December 11, 2019 at 3:17 PM ·

Today we did one of our kindness activities today...my favorite one 😍 Each student was given money to spend to buy food for the food bank. We went to Fareway, the students picked their own food items, we donated our change to the Salvation Army red kettle campaign and donated our food to our local food drive. It is great for the students to learn about giving and helping people who are in need. Not to mention they feel so good about themselves for helping others! Our hearts really grew today! We are blessed! #NHTribe spread kindness like kindergarten🥰
